Then junction with Easton St. Roof of Union Baptist Church just seen. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

Eight pensioners working at the Old People's Workshop, at 84a Easton St, High Wycombe. late 1950's
Group of about 8 pensioners working at the Old People's Workshop packing bags for Hoover vacuum cleaners was one of the jobs.

Group of pensioners standing in a passage, probably that by the Old People's Workshop at 84a, Easton St, High Wycombe. July 1964
Group of pensioners standing in a passage, probably at the back of 84a Easton St, which was used as an Old People's Workshop.

Looking SE, a view of the brick wall at the front of Tilecotes or Tilecote House in Oxford Rd, Marlow. 1990's
The brick wall at the front of Tilecotes or Tilecote House (visible beyond), in Oxford Rd.

Looking W, a view of the river Wye flowing past the District Council Offices, towards the S end of Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. January 1984
R.Wye flowing past the District Council Offices right, towards the S. end of Queen Victoria Rd. Seen through the trees the Police Station. On the left bank, not seen, is an award-winning paved and planted garden.

A view of a man and woman outside Turville Lodge, N. of Turville Park, Turville Heath. about 1900
A man and woman outside the ivy clad Turville Lodge, N.of Turville Park. Originally late c18, the brick built house has three chimney stacks and a metal roofed porch to both door and french windows. It was once the home of the head gardener. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking E, a view of the replacement for the old fountain in pedestrian area, and shops on E side of Frogmoor, High Wycombe. late 1980's
Foreground, replacement for the old fountain in pedestrian area. Shops on E side of Frogmoor - from left Popp's newsagent no. 14, Presto Cafe no. 12, entrance to Snooker Hall, Soft Spot no. 10 formerly Frogmoor Gift Shop, and Burtons Menswear.

Looking NW from the yard behind the Museum, a view of the rebuilding of a flint wall during refurbishment at Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1990
A man rebuilding a flint wall, part of the refurbishment of buildings to the rear of Wycombe Museum, formerly Castle Hill House. The wall became an enclosed flower bed near the Education Room. In background the roofs of houses in the Haystacks. Other views of this work on MHW02193 - 02206

Looking W, a view of the R.Thames and Marlow Weir, with All Saints Church and Marlow Bridge beyond. Marlow. c 1920
Marlow Weir and the Thames seen in foreground, with All Saints Church and the pillars of Marlow Bridge beyond.

Men and women enjoying a Christmas Party at the Old People's Workshop in 84a Easton St, High Wycombe. December 1964
Men and women seated around tables enjoying a Christmas Party at the Old People's Workshop in Easton St. Mrs B. Place the Secretary is seen centre. A man in military uniform stands at back left.

Looking N from Kingsmead Rd across the valley, a view of the bridge across the Back Stream leading onto the rugby pitches on Kings Mead, Loudwater. c 1980
A bridge across the Back Stream leading onto the rugby pitches on Kings Mead, viewed from Kingsmead Rd, E of the Rugby Club. Houses on London Rd. running W to E. On the skyline, houses in Hammersley Lane.

James Cave seen with a group of workers outside a factory building at Rye Paper Mill, London Rd, High Wycombe. c 1900?
Group of male workers with a dog pose outside a factory building at Rye Paper Mill. James Cave is marked with an 'X', seen second from right on the top row.

Looking NE, a view of the rear of Oxford Cottage with the roof of 'Tilecote House' beyond. Oxford Rd, Marlow. 1990's
The rear of Oxford Cottage and the roof of 'Tilecote House' just seen back left.

Pensioners at a tea break whilst working at the Old People's Workshop in Easton Street, High Wycombe. late 1950's
A group of pensioners enjoying a tea break whilst working at the Old People's Workshop.

Looking W, a view of the river Wye flowing under the commemorative bridge at the S end of Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. January 1984
R. Wye flowing under the commemorative bridge, given to the town in 1901 by Earl Carrington, at the S. end of Queen Victoria Rd. Beyond the bridge left the Liberal Club, behind the tower of the Fire Station and the British Legion Club. Right the Police Station.

Looking N/NW, a view across the churchyard to the S side of the Church of St Mary Magdalene at Great Hampden. before August 1905
View of the S side of the Church of St.Mary Magdalene at Hampden, with porch and tower to left. Adjacent to Hampden House.

Looking S, a view of a man cycling across a field with the Primitive Methodist Chapel in the background. Three Ways, Turville Heath. 1930's?
Man cycling across a field with the Primitive Methodist Chapel in the background. Another building, possibly a church, stands to the left. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking N/NE across the lawns, a summer view of the gardens and front of Wycombe Museum (formerly Castle Hill House), Priory Ave, High Wycombe. early 1990's
A summer view of the gardens and front of Wycombe Museum (formerly Castle Hill House). Three benches stand in the grounds. In the background, houses in The Haystacks.

Looking NE, a view of a breakdown vehicle righting a lorry outside the Post Office, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. March 1982
Breakdown vehicle from Five Alls Garage helps with the righting of a lorry outside the Post Office. It overturned after brake failure at the junction of Totteridge Rd and Amersham Hill. Lorry driver Robert Crompton and car driver Clifford Dawkins were unhurt. In foreground Library gardens, in background Post Office with Britannic Assurance, Terrys Gents Hairdresser and Connells Estate Agents to left. Then junction with Easton St. Roof of Union Baptist Church just seen. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

At the front door of Wycombe Museum, Roger Lawson speaking at the 25th Anniversary celebrations of the High Wycombe Soc. Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1994
Roger Lawson, Chairman of the High Wycombe Society, making a speech at the celebrations to mark 25 years of the Society. Behind is a cake and in the doorway of the Museum stands a small electronic keyboard. A banner hangs on the wall above a bench. Same event on MHW02382 -87, MHW02211 -13, MHW02188

Looking N from yard to rear of the Museum, a view of refurbishment of buildings including the Education Room off left. Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1990
Refurbishment of buildings to the rear of Wycombe Museum including the Education Room off left. Flint wall on left for flowerbeds. Behind the roofs of houses in The Haystacks. Other views of this work on MHW02193 - 02206

Looking E, the Post Office and Sunnyside are in the background as eight children pose for the camera on Northend Green, Northend, Turville. c 1910
Eight children pose for the camera on Northend Green. Beyond (centre) is the Post Office and village shop, with a house adjoining on right. A woman sits in a passenger carriage outside this house, while another walks past the house called Sunnyside. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking N from Oxford St, a view of the repaving of the central pedestrian area and construction of Chiltern Shopping Centre, Frogmoor, High Wycombe. c 1985
Frogmoor during repaving of pedestrian area and construction of Chiltern Shopping Centre. Shops on W. side Mercantile Credit nos. 3-5, Kentucky Fried Chicken, Peter Dominic wine merchants no. 13, Jumbo Discounts no. 33. Clock-tower in background formerly the Intimate Theatre, now (2007) offices. E side, Austin's Bed Centre np. 46. Front left an Information Board with town map and road signs to Headquarters Strike Command and Dovecot car-park.

Looking SW at junction of Desborough Rd/Desborough Ave, a funeral procession passes the Capital and Counties Bank. Desborough Rd, High Wycombe. early 1900's
Funeral procession with horse-drawn hearse and small military procession marching with reversed arms moves down Desborough Ave. and turns into Desborough Rd. A small crowd of bystanders looks on. On the SW corner of the junction stands the Capital and Counties bank.

A view of Brian Shirfield, Tom Pickett and Alf Chamberlain enjoying a drink in The Drovers PH, Drovers Lane, Southend, nr Turville. c 1960
In The Drovers public house, Brain Shirfield, Tom Pickett and Alf Chamberlain enjoying a drink. Alf's bag hangs on the wall. Part of an exhibition celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

A group of pensioners packing vacuum cleaner bags at the Old People's Workshop, Easton St, High Wycombe. late 1950's
Group of pensioners working at the Old People's Workshop packing vacuum cleaner bags for Hoover at 84a Easton St, bought with money from a local donor and the High Wycombe and District Housing Association.

mentions.ne_span: High Wycombe and District Housing Association

text:
Looking SE, a view of the Municipal Offices of Wycombe Borough Council in Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. 1973
The offices of Wycombe Borough Council in Queen Victoria Rd. Car parking in front of the offices. Right, in the trees, the buildings of Wycombe Abbey School. The R. Wye flows from right to left behind the wall beyond the offices.

Looking SE, a view of the entrance to the Chiltern Shopping Centre and adjacent shops on E side of Frogmoor, High Wycombe. late 1980's
The entrance to the Chiltern Shopping Centre and adjacent premises on E side of Frogmoor. From left, Granada TV Rentals, Hamells Petite ladies fashion and Next Ladies fashion. Decorations suggest Christmas time.

Looking NE, a view of the first floor window above the front door of Tilecotes, N of the junction of Cambridge Rd and Oxford Rd, Marlow. 1990's
View of first floor above front door (just visible) of Tilecotes, N. of junction of Oxford Rd and Cambridge Rd. The triple paned window stands in a bay. The door has pilasters on either side, a fanlight above and porch.

Looking W from a first floor window, an elevated view of the flooded back garden of Mrs Beaven in Chestnut Ave, High Wycombe. 1980
From a first floor window, an elevated view of the flooded back garden of Mrs Jaci Beaven in Chestnut Ave. In the background houses in Bassetsbury Lane.

The Red Lion from the portico of the Red Lion Hotel in the High St, on a trolley in a display at Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1990's
The Red Lion, originally erected in the 1820's on the portico of the Red Lion Hotel in the High St, on a trolley in a display at Wycombe Museum. It came to the Museum in 1985 having been some years at Hughenden Manor.

A view of a horse-drawn cart with a driver and boy, making a delivery of firewood at Northend, Turville. about 1920's
A horse drawn cart with a driver and boy, making a delivery of firewood. Standing by a wooden shed with a corrugated roof, and a house beyond. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

A view of scaffolding used in the refurbishment of buildings, with a sign to bodger's hut reconstruction at Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1990
Scaffolding used in the refurbishment of buildings to the rear of Wycombe Museum, formerly Castle Hill House. A notice on the wall shows the way to the reconstruction of a bodger's hut. Other views of this work on MHW02193 - 02206

A view of the scullery before refurbishment, showing the pump and a stone sink. Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. late 1980's?
In the scullery of Wycombe Museum before refurbishment, a pump and stone sink. A metal support for the ceiling is to the left.

Opposite Harlow Rd, looking NE, a view of houses on the N side of London Road with the R. Wye flowing on the south. London Rd, High Wycombe. c 1905
Houses on the N side of London Road with the R Wye flowing on S side. Just seen, set back from road, is The Nag's Head PH.

Looking W nr the junction of former Newland Meadow, a view of William Ives' grocery and provision shop, Desborough Rd, High Wycombe. c 1965
William Ives' grocery and provision shop 34 Desborough Rd, at the junction Rd with the former Newland Meadow. On the right Stewart and Arnold chocolate factory, and Rutland St leading off to the left

An exterior view of the back facade of Turville Park, Turville. 1960's?
Across the lawns, a view of the back facade of Turville Park with wings on either side, used as flats. Notes say 'used for a postcard'. Canopied conservatory to left of door. Part of an exhibition celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking N, a view of the frontage to the left of the front door of ' Tilecotes', N of the junction of Cambridge Rd and Oxford Rd, Marlow. 1990's
Front, left of front door, of ' Tilecotes' N of the junction of Oxford Rd. and Cambridge Rd. A red brick house with tiled roof, the walls covered with climbing plants.

An exterior view of the ivy clad walls at the back of Turville Park, Turville. 1930's?
Ivy clad back facade of Turville Park with wings on either side (used as a subject for a postcard). Canopied conservatory to left of door. Three large trees on lawns. Part of an exhibition celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking S towards junction with Holloway Lane, a view of a man passing by sheep grazing on land opposite the pond at Northend, Turville. 1920s?
A man walks by sheep grazing on land opposite the pond. Top right the Village Hall, centre to left of road a house called Sunnyside. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking N(?),a view of a porched doorway at the front of Tilecotes House standing N of the junction of Cambridge Rd and Oxford Rd, Marlow. 1990's
View of a porched doorway at the front of Tilecotes House, standing N of junction of Oxford Rd and Cambridge Rd.

A large group of pensioners doing light assembly work/packing at the Old People's Workshop, Easton St, High Wycombe. late 1950's
Group of pensioners working at the Old People's Workshop at 84a Easton St. bought with money from a local donor and the High Wycombe and District Housing Association.

mentions.ne_span: High Wycombe and District Housing Association

text:
Marc Meltonville, from Wycombe Museum, with a boy at a stand called Wycombe Museum is Full of Surprises. At Radnage School Fete, Radnage. June 1998
Marc Meltonville, an officer at Wycombe Museum, talking to a boy at Radnage School Fete at a stand called Wycombe Museum is Full of Surprises. On the table is a 'feely box' with four holes together with pamphlets about the Museum.

Looking NE from nr Dovecote Rd, a view across land at N of Frogmoor cleared for redevelopment with former Intimate Theatre boarded up. Frogmoor, High Wycombe. 1960's?
Land at N of Frogmoor cleared for redevelopment and building of Dovecot car park. The former Intimate Theatre now boarded up. Peters Hairdresser E side of Frogmoor. Priory Rd School just seen behind railway viaduct.

Looking NE across the gardens, a view of an audience seated ready to watch an open-air performance of Carmen. Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1994
An audience seated in a semi-circle ready to watch an open-air performance of Carmen on a stage set up in the gardens at the front of Wycombe Museum. Stage light are set up and three drums stand left.

Looking NW between 'Hand of Flowers' and Spinfield Lane, a view of a red brick-built house at 168 West St, Marlow. 1990's?
A red brick-built house with decorative brickwork above the windows at 168 West St. adjoining the terrace of houses seen on RHW02674. A long garden to the road.

Looking NE, a view of the Municipal Offices of Wycombe Borough Council, the R. Wye and the commemorative bridge in Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. 1970's
The offices of Wycombe Borough Council in Queen Victoria Rd. seen from S. end. The R. Wye in foreground flowing under the commemorative bridge presented to the town by 1st Earl Carrington to honour the 'prosperous and glorious reign' of Queen Victoria. Left the Police Station.

Looking NW from the yard behind the Museum, a view of refurbishment of buildings including the Education Room, Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1990
Refurbishment of buildings to the rear of Wycombe Museum, formerly Castle Hill House. Foreground the flint wall later enclosed a flower bed with the Education Room adjacent. In the background houses in The Haystacks. Other views of this work on MHW02193 - 02206

Nancy Hall with others at a Christmas Party, probably at the Old People's Workshop, 84a Easton St, High Wycombe., 1960's
Nancy Hall, wife of the Member of Parliament sitting with others at the top table? at a Christmas Party, probably one held for pensioners at the Old People's Workshop at Easton St

View of machinery, probably a generator and its associated switchgear in the General Hospital, Queen Alexandra Rd, High Wycombe. late 1960's
View of machinery (probably a generator) and its associated switchgear in High Wycombe General Hospital.

View of a Royal Shooting Party including Viscount Curzon, 3rd Earl Howe, Countess Howe, the future George V and Queen Mary. Penn House Farm, Penn. late 1890's?
Royal Shooting Party outside Penn House Farm Far left, standing Viscount Curzon, unknown, 3rd Earl Howe, Countess Howe, unknown, the future George V. The future Queen Mary is seated left.

Looking NW between 'Hand of Flowers' and Spinfield Lane, a view of a terrace of four flint-built houses, 162 and 164 West St, Marlow. 1990's
A terrace of four flint built houses with red brick decoration around windows and doors and a slate roof, possibly 18C or early 19C.

Looking NE, a view of a white horse owned by the Langford family, standing on the Green at Northend, Turville, 1940s.
A white shire horse owned by the Langford family, tethered on Northend Green. This may be one called Dapple, or a descendant of his. 
The photograph dates from the 1940's because the bus in the background is a Second World War utility one. Operated by House's of Watlington, it would be on their Watlington - Northend - Henley route. House had four of these buses dating from 1942 to 1945.

The photograph was part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Group of women, men and children on a group outing posed in a charabanc. location unknown. 1930's?
Group of women, men and children on a group outing posed in a charabanc. In the background are terraced houses and a sign for the Victoria Steam Laundry.

Looking NW, a view of the front door of 'Tilecotes', N of the junction of Cambridge Rd and Oxford Rd, Marlow. 1990's
The front door of ' Tilecotes' N of the junction of Oxford Rd. and Cambridge Rd. On either side pilasters and a fanlight with 'spider web' design above. A lamp hangs from the triangular pediment. Two windows on either side of the door and one above. The red brick is covered with ivy.

Looking NE, a view of a man from Five Alls Garage helping to right a lorry overturned outside the Post Office, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. March 1982
A man from Five Alls Garage helps to right a lorry overturned outside the Post Office after brake failure at the junction of Totteridge Rd and Amersham Hill. Lorry driver Robert Crompton and car driver Clifford Dawkins were unhurt. Another breakdown vehicle behind. Airbags seen to right of lorry. In foreground Library gardens, in background the Post Office with Britannic Assurance, Terrys Gents Hairdresser and Connells Estate Agents to left. Then junction with Easton St. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

Looking N, a view of The Bell public house and the former Intimate Theatre, boarded up prior to redevelopment. Frogmoor, High Wycombe. 1977
The former Intimate Theatre boarded up prior to redevelopment, formerly the Institute of Science and Arts Sign for Bond's Laundry hangs on right. Behind, Frogmoor Motor Company building stands in front of the railway viaduct. Left the Bell public house.

Looking NW, just N of Spinfield Lane, a view of two semi-detached flint cottages with brick dressings at 172, 174 and 176 West St, Marlow. 1990s?
Two semi-detached flint cottages with brick dressings at 172, 174 and 176 West St. To the N is a modern house. On the left a road or access to rear.

Looking NE, a view of The Municipal Offices of Wycombe Borough Council in Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. 1973
The offices of Wycombe Borough Council in Queen Victoria Rd, seen from the SW. Beyond left, the Post Office building.

Looking N across the lawn, a detail of a deckchair painted with an individual design. Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1991
On the lawn in front of Wycombe Museum, a deckchair painted with individual design, part of a larger display. Four others in background. Three benches stand in front of the Museum, formerly Castle Hill House. Background left, house in the Haystacks. This exhibition on MHW02354 - 02362

Detail view of the M.B.E. Insignia awarded to Jack Scruton (then Hon. Sec. of the High Wycombe Society) in the Birthday Honours List 1991.
The M.B.E. Insignia awarded to Jack Scruton, Honorary Secretary of the High Wycombe Society in the Birthday Honours List. Official notification came four days after his death on 1st June 1991.

At Penn Bottom Farm, a view of Mr Crispin Winter, (Earl Howe's Bailiff) with his son and 'Free' Fryer, posed before a portable steam engine. Penn. c 1902
Mr Crispin Winter (centre), Earl Howe's Bailiff at Penn Bottom Farm with his son and 'Free' Fryer, a Farmhand. The portable steam engine was used on the farm.

View of two large boilers in the boiler house of High Wycombe General Hospital, Queen Alexandra Rd, High Wycombe. late 1960's
Two oil-fired boilers in boiler house of High Wycombe General Hospital. Entrance to the boiler room was off the service yard accessed directly from Queen Alexandra Rd.

A hay-making scene, four men and a boy stand on top of a hay-cart near Nairne Cottage, Northend, Turville. about 1920's
Four men holding tools and a boy stand on top of a hay-cart at Nairne cottage. A white horse stands in harness. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking N across the lawn, a detail of a deckchair painted with chair design. Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1991
On the lawn in front of Wycombe Museum, a deckchair painted with chair design, part of a larger display, the canvases decorated individually. Four other deckchairs in background. Two benches stand in front of the Museum, formerly Castle Hill House. This exhibition on MHW02354 - 02362

Looking E, a view of Frogmoor Gift Shop (Soft Spot), and the entrance to the Snooker and Billiards Hall, Frogmoor, High Wycombe. c 1988
View of Frogmoor Gift Shop no. 10, named Soft Spot selling computer games and books. Name changed after 1987. Also the entrance to the Snooker and Billiards hall above.

Looking E, a view of a man from Five Alls Garage helping to right a lorry overturned outside the Post Office, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. March 1982
A man from Five Alls Garage helps to right a lorry overturned outside the Post Office after brake failure at the junction of Totteridge Rd and Amersham Hill. Lorry driver Robert Crompton and car driver Clifford Dawkins were unhurt. Another breakdown vehicle behind. In foreground Library gardens, in background the Post Office with Britannic Assurance, Terrys Gents Hairdresser and Connells Estate Agents to left. Junction with Easton St seen on left. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

A view of pensioners working at the Old People's Workshop in Easton Street, High Wycombe. late 1950's
A group of pensioners working at the Old People's Workshop. Packing bags for Hoover vacuum cleaners was one of the tasks.

Looking E, View of front creeper clad elevation of 'Sunnyside', standing N. of the Post Office and fronting The Green, Northend, Turville. 1930's?
View of front creeper clad elevation of Sunnyside, standing N. of the Post Office and fronting The Green. The centre part is flint and the r.h. side brick. Just see. right a carpenter's workshop, the Pitcher family business. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking NW from just beyond the 'Hand of Flowers', a view of two 18C(?) semi-detached brick cottages, 140 and 142 West St, Marlow, 1990's
Two 18C (?) semi-detached brick cottages with tiled roof and original window frames. The left-hand one is painted white with black shutters and the porch is supported by decorative iron work. A road on the left leads to modern housing beyond.

Looking E between Desborough Ave and Short St, a view of shops and shoppers on the N side of Desborough Rd, High Wycombe. before October 1906
Shoppers and a horse and cart seen in Desborough Rd from junction with Desborough Ave to junction with Short St. Walter Stephenson's grocer shop in background.

Equipment in the Operating Theatre of the General Hospital, Queen Alexandra Rd, High Wycombe. April 1969
Operating theatre with trolley and other equipment in High Wycombe General Hospital. The operating theatres were built on the N. facing side of the upper ground floor built as part of Phase II extension.

Looking N across the lawns and gardens, a view of the front of Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1980's?
Front view of Wycombe Museum, formerly Castle Hill House with gardens in foreground. Two benches stand in front. On the right houses in the Greenway. The Museum gardens before restoration [md]

Looking NW, a view of the river Wye to the west of the commemorative bridge at the S end of Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. Autumn 1983
R. Wye seen NW of the commemorative bridge at the S end of Queen Victoria Rd. Left, the Liberal Club with tower of Fire Station behind. Right the Police Station.

Looking E, a view of a swan on the Lake, with bungalows E of the (now) Lancaster Arts Centre seen behind. Wycombe Abbey Grounds, High Wycombe. Dec 1983
Swan on the Lake in the grounds of Wycombe Abbey School. Chalet bungalows E of the (now) Lancaster Arts Centre seen behind.

A head-and-shoulder portrait of Jack Scruton (then Hon. Sec. of the High Wycombe Society) with his M.B.E. medal superimposed. location unknown. after 1991
A head- and- shoulders portrait of Jack Scruton, Honorary Secretary of the High Wycombe Society with his M.B.E. medal superimposed. His M.B.E. was awarded in the Birthday Honours List in June 1991.

Looking E, a view of Popp's newsagent and part of the Presto Cafe, Frogmoor, High Wycombe. c 1988
Popp's newsagent on 14 Frogmoor, E side, and Presto Cafe (no.12) to S

Looking E, a view of a lorry restored to its wheels after overturning outside the Post Office, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. March 1982
An articulated lorry standing across Queen Victoria Rd. having overturned outside the Post Office after brake failure at the junction of Totteridge Rd and Amersham Hill. Lorry driver Robert Crompton and car driver Clifford Dawkins were unhurt. Two breakdown vehicles attended, one from Five Alls Garage. Airbags seen right of lorry. In foreground Library gardens, in background Post Office with Britannic Assurance, Terrys Gents Hairdresser and Connells Estate Agents. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

Looking E, a view of the river Wye flowing past Wycombe District Council offices, and into the culvert under Abbey Way, High Wycombe. January 1984
R. Wye flowing past Wycombe District Council offices (left) and then into a culvert under Abbey Way. Seen between the two cars, the former Health Centre building.

View of a group of pensioners and others who worked at the Old People's Workshop. Outside a building in the American Camp, Daws Hill, High Wycombe. July 1955
Group of pensioners and others posed outside a building in the American Camp at Daws Hill. The pensioners were part of a group who worked at the Old People's Workshop.

A tinted postcard view of the River Thames near Bourne End. before July 1906
Postcard view of the R. Thames near Bourne End. Bank on right has a house with conservatory and gardens down to the river. Bank on left has a small boat moored.

Equipment in the resuscitation room of the General Hospital, Queen Alexandra Rd, High Wycombe. April 1969
Equipment in the resuscitation room of High Wycombe General Hospital including resuscitation trolley; Barnet ventilator; East Radcliffe automatic blood pressure recorder; East Radcliffe ventilator, and Boyle anaesthetic machine.

A river, probably the R. Wye, flowing past a factory building with a wall on the N side and vegetation on the S side. High Wycombe? 1980's?
A river, probably the R. Wye, flowing past a factory building with a wall on the N side and vegetation on the S side.

Looking N across the lawns, a view of the Museum and gardens blanketed with snow. Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. post 1990
Wycombe Museum and gardens blanketed with snow, post restoration. Two benches stand in front of the Museum, formerly Castle Hill House, and another to the left.

From the gardens at Rayners, a view of a wedding group at the marriage of Louisa, daughter of Sir Philip Rose. Tylers Green. 1868
A wedding group gathered outside Rayners at the marriage of Louisa, daughter of Sir Philip Rose.

Looking W?, a view of a man with a bicycle in front of a cottage, with Mr.Grover's shoe shop in the background. Church Rd, Tylers Green. c 1914
A man with a bicycle stands in front of a cottage in Church Rd. In the background is a group by Mr. Grover's shoe shop.

Looking E, a view along the back stream E of The Dyke, with houses on Keep Hill Rd beyond. The Rye, High Wycombe. Autumn 1983
A view along the back stream (continuation of the Dyke) E of the waterfall, with houses on Keep Hill Rd in the background.

Looking NE, a view of a lorry restored to its wheels after overturning outside the Post Office, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. March 1982
An articulated lorry standing across Queen Victoria Rd. after overturning outside the Post Office after brake failure at the junction of Totteridge Rd and Amersham Hill. Lorry driver Robert Crompton and car driver Clifford Dawkins were unhurt.Two breakdown vehicles attended, one from Five Alls Garage. In foreground Library gardens, in background Post Office with Britannic Assurance, Terrys Gents Hairdresser and Connells Estate Agents to left. Then junction with Easton St. Roof of Union Baptist Church just seen. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

Looking NE, a view of vintage cars in a procession marking the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II. Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. June 1953
Crowds watching a procession of vintage cars turning from High St. into Queen Victoria Rd, part of the celebrations marking the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II. Vera Williams dress shop in background. Seen also on BFP01786

Looking NW across the lawns, a view of nine deckchairs (some occupied by the public), part of a larger display at Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1991
On the lawn in front of Wycombe Museum, members of the public and nine deckchairs, part of a larger display, the canvases decorated with individual designs. Three benches in the background. A statue behind left-hand bench. This exhibition on MHW02354 - 02362

Looking N from an elevated position nr junction with Queen Sq, a view of Frogmoor Gardens with shops on either side. Frogmoor, High Wycombe. early 1900's
Frogmoor Gardens lined with trees and with fountain in centre, shops and businesses on either side. Sign for Hare and Hound public house on E side. Horse trough with street vendor alongside, left. Dome of Institute of Science and Arts seen background.

mentions.ne_span: Dome of Institute of Science and Arts

text:
Looking E, a view of a swan on the Lake, with bungalows E of the (now) Lancaster Arts Centre seen behind. Wycombe Abbey Grounds, High Wycombe. Dec 1983
Swan on the Lake in the grounds of Wycombe Abbey School. Chalet bungalows E of the (now) Lancaster Arts Centre seen behind.

View of a small stream flowing between banks of vegetation. location unknown. 1980's?
A small stream flowing between banks of vegetation.

Looking N.E. on the B474, a view of No. 5 (Penn) Platoon, 'B' Company, 5th Bucks Battalion Home Guard, outside The Crown PH, Penn. 1944
No. 5 (Penn) Platoon, 'B' Company, 5th Bucks Battalion Home Guard, outside The Crown PH in 1944. Left ,a sign gives mileages on the B474 to Beaconsfield, Slough and to Forty Green. Two cars seen right.

Looking NW?, a winter view of young limes planted along Lime Avenue, running SE/NW to the east of Turville Park House. Turville Heath, 1920's?
Winter view of young limes planted along Lime Avenue, running SE/NW to the east of Turville Park House. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

View of Bill Rockall working at a pole lathe in a reproduction of a bodger's hut, at Summer Heath, Turville? 1960's?
Bill Rockall working at a pole lathe in a reproduction of a bodger's hut, at Summer Heath?

Looking NE from outside the Library, a view of an overturned lorry being righted with airbags. Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. March 1982
An overturned articulated lorry being righted with airbags. After brake failure at the junction of Totteridge Rd and Amersham Hill the lorry overturned outside the Post Office. Lorry driver Robert Crompton and car driver Clifford Dawkins were unhurt. Junction of Queen Victoria Rd and Crendon St in background. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

Looking SE, a view of many girls and boys lined up outside the School, after it had been extended. School Rd, Tylers Green. c 1911
Girls and boys lined up outside the School, seen after the extension was added

A view of families walking by a stream with parkland beyond. location unknown. 1960's?
Families walking by a steam with parkland beyond. Not the Rye.

A river, possibly the R. Wye, flowing through a field with a road and hedges beyond. location unknown. 1980's?
A river, possibly the R. Wye, flowing through field with a road and hedges beyond.

Group of six women in uniform and a young man in naval uniform pose in a garden. location unknown. about 1914
Group of six women, uniformly dressed in mob-caps and overalls, and a young man in naval uniform pose in a garden. The women are probably war-workers, the seaman appears to be from '...Valkyrie..'

Looking NE, a view of four cars driving through flood waters in Chestnut Avenue, High Wycombe. 1980
Four cars driving through flood waters in Chestnut Ave. The front car has the number MYV 783L. Four semi-detached houses behind. In the background a single storey building painted green.

Looking N across the lawns, a view of thirteen deckchairs, part of a larger display at Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1991
On the lawn in front of Wycombe Museum, thirteen deckchairs, part of a larger display, the canvases decorated with individual designs. A noticeboard stands in the porch. In front of the Museum, formerly Castle Hill House, are three benches. Behind left, house in The Haystacks. This exhibition on MHW02354 - 02362

Looking NE from the junction of Tancred Rd/Disraeli Crescent, a view across Hughenden Rd to the Green Hill area, Hughenden. 1970's?
From the junction of Tancred Rd. and Disraeli Crescent, a view across Hughenden Rd to Green Hill, with Earl Close off right. From Hughenden Rd running N/S housing on Green Hill zigzags upward right. Housing on hill left is Brands Hill Ave.

View of a young Bill Rockall and his father using a two-man saw to cut a tree trunk on Summer Heath. Turville Heath. 1950's?
Young Bill Rockall and his father using a two-man saw to cut a tree trunk on Summer Heath. In the background a car. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking SE, a view along Lime Avenue which runs SE/NW near Turville Park House, Turville Heath. 1920's?
View along Lime Avenue, which runs SE/NW, to the east of Turville Park House. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Probably looking W, a view of paths running downhill in Green Hill Woods, off Hughenden Rd. High Wycombe. c 1970
View of paths running downhill in Green Hill Woods with small trees on either side.

Looking N, an exterior view of nurses' flats in the accommodation blocks at the General Hospital, Barracks Rd, High Wycombe. late 1960's
Staff accommodation blocks at High Wycombe General Hospital with nurses' flat facing and flats for junior medical staff leading off left.

Looking W, a view of Mrs Jaci Beaven's back garden under water after a flood. Chestnut Ave, High Wycombe, 1980
Mrs Jaci Beaven's back garden in Chestnut Ave, under water after a flood. In the background houses in Bassetsbury Lane see also HWS02607 and 02610

A river, possibly the R. Wye, flowing between banks of vegetation. location unknown. 1980's?
A river, possibly the R. Wye, flowing through banks of vegetation

Looking E from the stage, a view of two workmen and another during the refurbishment of the auditorium in the Town Hall, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. July 1973
Two workmen and another during the refurbishment of the auditorium in the Town Hall, viewed from the stage.

A river, probably the R. Wye, passing through two adjacent tunnels. Possibly Bowden Mill, London Rd, High Wycombe. 1980's?
A river, probably the R. Wye, passing through two adjacent tunnels. Possibly Bowden Mill?

A group of men, women and children pose during a celebratory meal, possibly at Christmas. location unknown. late 1940's?
A group of men, women and children pose during a celebratory meal in a hall, possibly a church hall. Some at the far end are in fancy dress including a man dressed as Winston Churchill and another as Father Christmas. This latter, together with the greenery and streamers suggest a Christmas celebration.

Looking E, a view from Hughenden Park across Hughenden Road to Green Hill beyond. Hughenden. 1970's?
View from Hughenden Park across Hughenden Rd. with houses on E side and Green Hill beyond. Hughenden Stream running N-S crossed by bridge.

Looking E, a view of a man from Five Alls Garage helping to right a lorry overturned outside the Post Office, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. March 1982
A man from Five Alls Garage helps to right a lorry overturned outside the Post Office after brake failure at the junction of Totteridge Rd and Amersham Hill. Lorry driver Robert Crompton and car driver Clifford Dawkins were unhurt. Another breakdown vehicle behind. In foreground Library gardens, in background the Post Office with Britannic Assurance, Terrys Gents Hairdresser and Connells Estate Agents to left. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

Looking N? in the grounds of Wycombe Abbey School, a view of a coot swimming on the Lake. Wycombe Abbey Grounds, High Wycombe, Dec 1983
A coot swimming on the Lake in the grounds of Wycombe Abbey School. A brick wall and buildings seen beyond

Looking SW, a view of two cars outside the White Hart public house as their occupants pose for the camera. Northend, Turville. c 1930
Two cars outside the White Hart public house as their occupants pose for the camera. A man and woman stand at the gate to the public house which has timber framing and a tiled roof. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking E, a view of houses (Nos. 34 - 48) originally built on allotments to S side of New Road, Tylers Green. c 1933
Houses on the S side of New Road, built on allotments 1925 - 30, seen here about 1933.

Looking SW at the W end of the Rye, a view of three women and three men planting a tree. The Rye, High Wycombe. March 1979
Three women and three men, including one from Wycombe District Council, planting a tree on the W end of the Rye. Behind the fence the grounds of Wycombe Abbey School.

Looking N across the lawns, a view of thirteen deckchairs, part of a larger display at Wycombe Museum, Priory Ave, High Wycombe. 1991
On the lawn in front of Wycombe Museum, thirteen deckchairs, part of a larger display, the canvases decorated with individual designs. A noticeboard stands in the porch. In front of the Museum, formerly Castle Hill House, are three benches, another to left. Behind left, houses in The Haystacks. This exhibition on MHW02354 - 02362

Looking SE, a view of premises at the junction of Easton St and Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. about 1970
The E side of Queen Victoria Rd, seen at its junction with Easton St. From left, General Accident Fire and Life Assurance, Gas Centre, J.S.Davy and Son, Britannic Assurance Co. Ltd. and the Post Office. Road signs indicating left Oxford, London, Marlow, Wycombe General Hospital and car park.

mentions.ne_span: General Accident Fire and Life Assurance

text:
A river, possibly the R. Wye, flowing through banks of vegetation with a pillar to the left. location unknown. 1980's?
A river, possibly the R. Wye, flowing through banks of vegetation. Left, a pillar.

Looking E, a view of a man supervising the uprighting of a lorry overturned outside the Post Office, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. March 1982
A man supervises the uprighting of an overturned articulated lorry. After brake failure at the junction of Totteridge Rd and Amersham Hill the lorry overturned outside the Post Office. Lorry driver Robert Crompton and car driver Clifford Dawkins were unhurt. Two breakdown vehicles attended, one on left from Five Alls Garage. In foreground Library gardens, in background the Post Office with Britannic Assurance, Terrys Gents Hairdresser and Connells Estate Agents to left. Same event on RHW02336 - 02347

Looking SE, a view of premises on the corner of Easton St and Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe, about 1972
Premises on the corner of Easton St and Queen Victoria Rd. From left, Martin and Pole (estate agents), Same Day cleaners, R and P Mendy (gas appliances and showroom), J.S. Davy and Son (stationers). Traffic signs for Oxford, London, Marlow, 'car park' and Wycombe General Hospital outlined in marker pen.

Portrait of Jack Scruton, M.B.E, the then Honorary Secretary of the High Wycombe Society. location unknown. 1980's?
Photo portrait showing the head of Jack Scruton, M.B.E. At the time, Honorary Secretary of the High Wycombe Society.

Looking N?, a view of the R.Wye, flowing in two channels past sluice gates. Possibly immediately west of Bassetsbury Mill? Bassetsbury area, High Wycombe. Autumn 1983
A river, probably the R.Wye, flowing in two channels past sluice gates with vegetation on each side. In the background a building, possibly a cottage. This may be the area immediately west of Bassetsbury Mill

A group of women, children and men on a Mothers' Outing pose in a charabanc in front of church tower. location unknown. 1930's?
A group of women, children and men on Mothers' Outing pose in a charabanc. This has the name Dulcie on the side and the number HJ3701. In the background the stone-built tower of a church and a wall.

A view of Barnes Corner Shop at the junction of St John's Rd and New Rd, Tylers Green. about 1940
The corner shop owned by L.F.Barnes in the 1940s. Harold Wheeler worked for Mr Barnes at that time.

View of Bill Rockall splitting logs outside a reproduction of a bodger's hut, at Summer Heath, Turville? 1960's?
Outside his bodger's hut, Bill Rockall uses a beetle and wedge to split logs for chair legs. The external working of the pole lathe seen, and a shave horse, two-handled saw and a wheelbarrow. Right, a stack of chair legs. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking NW, a view of fly posting on disused shops at 26/27 Easton St, High Wycombe. 1978
Fly posting on disused shops at nos. 26 and 27 Easton St. Car park for college vehicles on site of former Taylors Sweet factory at no. 25.

Looking N, a view of the District Council Offices, seen from the garden S of the river Wye, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. 1986
The building of the District Council Offices opened in 1932, seen from the garden S of the R Wye. The Post Office is seen behind left.

Looking W, a view of traffic moving past the traffic lights in Abbey Way, High Wycombe. February 1979
Traffic moving along Abbey Way past the traffic lights. To the right (on N side), the Law Courts. Centre, the offices of Wycombe District Council. Just seen left Wycombe General Hospital, with Tom Burt's Hill beyond.

Looking N, a view of the South front of Turville Court, Turville Heath,. c 1932
South front of Turville Court showing delicate metal work to balcony, and bay on left. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking N, a view of the sign hanging outside 'The Drovers' PH in Drovers Lane, Southend, nr Turville. about 1960
A sign for The Drover public house (Henley Brewery) with the building just visible to the left. Drovers Lane here runs N, with trees on either side. Part of an exhibition celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking NW?, a summer view of a distant car travelling along Lime Avenue, near Turville Park House, Turville Heath. 1920's?
A distant car travels along Lime Avenue, seen in summer. The Avenue runs SE/NW to the east of Turville Park House. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking SE at the junction of Church Rd/Hammersley Lane, a view of a group outside St Margaret's Church, Tylers Green. 1905
Looking SE, a view of St.Margaret's Church with seven people standing in Church Rd. Left, a signpost with mileages to Penn, Beaconsfield and Penn Street and others.

Looking S/SE from alongside the fire station, a view of traffic on a mini-roundabout, part of the larger roundabout at Abbey Way, High Wycombe. late 1970's
Traffic moving around a mini-roundabout, part of the larger Abbey Way roundabout. Wycombe Abbey School seen in background.

Looking W, a view of the E elevation of Turville Court, showing a castle-style tower. Turville Heath. c 1930
East elevation of Turville Court, showing castle-style tower added by Mrs Conway. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking NW across the Rye, a view of two boys fishing from the S bank of the Dyke, The Rye, High Wycombe. 1980's?
Two boys fishing from the S bank of the Dyke. Beyond, three spectators watch a football game on the Rye. Housing along the London Road runs from the Friends' Meeting House right to the towers of Trinity Church. Next, the former grammar school building in Easton St. and the roof of Wycombe District Council Offices.

A view of erosion of the south bank of the Dyke, The Rye, High Wycombe. 1987
A view of erosion of the bank of the Dyke.

Looking NE, a view of the extension to the District Council Offices and the R.Wye, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. 1986
The new extension to the District Council Offices seen with the original building, opened in 1932. The R. Wye flows in the foreground.

A river, probably the R. Wye back stream, flowing next to a road which bends to the left. High Wycombe? 1980's?
A river, probably the R. Wye back stream, flowing next to a road which bends to the left. The road has a 20m.p.h. and 'Trespassers Will Be Prosecuted' signs. On the left behind a hedge stands a cottage. In the background a valley slope with houses.

Looking W, a view of horse-buses waiting at the railway yard, opposite the Railway Temperance Hotel. Amersham Hill, High Wycombe. c 1905
From the railway yard, the junction of Crendon St, Amersham Hill and Castle St. The Railway Temperance Hotel to the right on Amersham Hill. Four buses wait outside Weston's (carriage builder) in the Railway Tavern Yard.

Looking E, a view of the West window and ivy-clad West wall of St.Margaret's Church, Church Road, Tylers Green. c 1920?
St.Margaret's Church. The ivy-clad west window with bell above. To the right, the N porch and path with street lamp. The church was built in 1854.

A view of members of the Rockall family with visitors from London, posing in woods near Summer Heath, Turville Heath. c 1900
Members of the Rockall family with visitors from London, seen sitting on logs in woodland at Summer Heath. The visitors may be Elizabeth Cook (centre back?), daughter of Samuel Rockall (snr), and her five children. (Information from Freda Murray) Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking E towards Saffron Rd, a view of the back of the (then) annexe of Wycombe and Amersham College, Easton St, High Wycombe. 1986
Back of the then annexe of Wycombe and Amersham College, formerly the Royal Grammar School. Beyond, the end of building of Trinity United Church, a car park, and facing, a house in Saffron Rd.

Looking N, a view of the employees of Mr J.Bond (builder) in a four-horse brake at the start of their outing to Kew. Oxford Rd, High Wycombe. 16 Jul 1898
The house with the glazed structure was then the home of Mr J.Bond, builder - 2 years later he moved to Totteridge Avenue as a consequence of the development of Bellfield Road for access to the new railway goods yard.

Looking S, a view of two floats in a procession marking the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II, passing the Post Office in Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. June 1953
Two floats, part of the celebrations marking the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II, pass the Post Office. The foremost float has characters in fancy dress and is surmounted with a crown. The other floats has nurses and a red cross. Beyond the Post Offices stands Christchurch Sunday School.

Looking SE, a view of seven men and women dressed in rustic costumes standing beside a horse and decorated cart at an event on The Rye, High Wycombe. 1980's
Seven men and women dressed in rustic costumes standing beside a horse and decorated cart at an event on the Rye, possibly the Wycombe Show. Third from left in mop cap is Myra King, Leader of the Pann Mill Group, High Wycombe Society.

A river, probably the R.Wye, flowing round a bend with possibly factory premises on the left. High Wycombe? 1980's?
A river, probably the R.Wye, flowing round a bend. On the left a path with brick wall and a gate restricting further access, suggesting factory premises. On the right part of the bank has a wall.

A view of Cyril Baddeley and his assistants outside 'Baddeley and Son Supply Stores'. Elm Rd, Penn. c 1920
Cyril Baddeley stands outside his shop, Baddeley and Son Supply Stores. Left Jimmy Palmer, right Harold Wheeler, both shop assistants. Clothing, shoes, drapery, grocery provisions and garden forks were amongst the items for sale.

Looking SW, a spring view of Mrs Jaci Beaven's back garden in Chestnut Ave, High Wycombe. 1980
Mrs Jaci Beaven's back garden in Chestnut Ave in the Spring. In the background, houses in Bassetsbury Lane and the trees S of the Rye. see also HWS02608 and 02610

A view showing Willie Rockall and another man with four donkeys laden with wood at Turville Heath. c 1930?
Willie Rockall and another man with four donkeys laden with wood at Turville Heath. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking SE from above Bellfield, a panoramic view across the town from above the railway line towards the parish church, High Wycombe. c 1900
View across High Wycombe town centre with single track railway line on left crossing the viaduct over Temple End. All Saints Church in centre, Wesleyan Methodist Church to left, Primitive Methodist Chapel with National School to right in White Hart St. Former priory Road School to the left.

Looking SW, a view of two women playing tennis on the lawn in front of the E side of Wycombe Abbey School, High Wycombe. c 1900
Two women playing tennis on the lawn in front of the E side of Wycombe Abbey School. Two others sit by the windows. Also seen on BFP03458

Looking NE, a view of a crowd watching a procession marking the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II. Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. June 1953
A crowd watches a procession, with children in fancy dress, moving S. down Queen Victoria Rd, as part of the celebrations marking the Coronation of Queen Elizabeth II. The junction with Easton St seen right. Also on BFP04471 and BFP33259

Looking NW, a view of the Library and its extension towards the Town Hall, both decorated with flags. Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. 1937?
W. side of Queen Victoria Rd. showing the Library and its extension linking it to the Town Hall. The extension was opened in July 1937. The Town Hall and Library are decked with a variety of flags, possibly for the Coronation of George VI in May 1937. Just seen left the Police Station. Right the shops in the High St.

Looking SE from the R.Wye, a view of three men walking beside the river with the Rye beyond. High Wycombe. 1970's?
Three men walk beside the R. Wye just E. of Pann Mill. Beyond the Rye with the buildings of Holywell Mead Swimming Pool centre, and the housing of Warren Wood behind. Left Bassetsbury Manor and houses in Bassetsbury Lane

A view of Tom Hutton, Tom Pickett and Alf Chamberlain enjoying a drink in The Drovers PH, Drovers Lane, Southend, nr Turville. c 1960
Tom Hutton, Tom Pickett and Alf Chamberlain enjoying a beer in The Drovers public house. Alf's bag hangs on the wall. Part of an exhibition celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking E, a view of 'Sunnyside' with a carpenter's workshop alongside. The Green, Northend, Turville. 1920's?
Front view of Sunnyside, a house with a carpenter's workshop on right, the Pitcher family business. Sunnyside stands N of the Post Office and fronts The Green. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking SW across the lake, a view of the E front of Wycombe Abbey School. Abbey Grounds, High Wycombe. c 1960
The E front of Wycombe Abbey School, seen across the lake, with several mature trees in the grounds.

A postcard view advertising The Dog Tavern, on the W side of Hazlemere Rd at its junction with Meadow Walk, Tylers Green. date unknown
A postcard advertising The Dog Tavern, pulled down in 1965. The Dog sold Simonds beer.

Looking W/NW, a view of a procession carrying a banner of Oxford Road Sunday School, walking towards Frogmoor, along Oxford St, High Wycombe. c 1895
Procession, mainly of boys, carrying a banner for Oxford Road Sunday School walking towards Frogmoor. On N side is Bristow Millinery at no. 45, and a public house sign in the background.

Looking SW from the junction with the High St, a view of the Town Hall and W side of Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. c 1920
W. side of Queen Victoria Rd with the Town Hall seen from its junction with the High St on right. The land N. of the Town Hall was where the Library was subsequently built.

View of a boy and girl paddling in a river, possibly the R. Wye at The Rye, High Wycombe. 1960's?
A boy and girl paddling in a river, possibly the R. Wye. Behind them vegetation and a brick wall.

Looking W, a view of the R. Wye as it flows alongside the A40 between Rye Mill and Pann Mill, The Rye, High Wycombe. Autumn 1983
The R. Wye as it flows alongside the A40 between Rye Mill and Pann Mill. Beyond the vegetation on S bank is seen the roof of Wycombe General Hospital

Looking E, a view of the house incorporating the Post Office and village store in Northend, Turville. c 1930?
Front of the house incorporating the  Post Office and village store. Signs with 'Northend Post Office' over the door, and 'Family Grocer' above the window. The Post Office portion is flint faced, whilst the main  house is brick with a porch. Part of an exhibition in October 1994 celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Postcard with four views of High Wycombe - High St, Wycombe Abbey School, Town Hall and Library, and The Dyke on The Rye. High Wycombe. 1950's?
Postcard showing four views of High Wycombe. Top left, the High St, viewed from E with shops, a garage and the Guildhall. Top right, Wycombe Abbey School and grounds seen from SE. Bottom left, the Town Hall and Library on left with District Council Offices on right, in Queen Victoria Rd. Bottom left, The Dyke on The Rye seen from boathouse at W end. In centre, a lucky black cat motif.

Looking NE, a view of a group of men watching a demonstration by a market trader outside the Little Market House, High St, High Wycombe. 1900's
Rear view of a group of men watching a demonstration by a market trader outside the Little Market House. Beyond are the buildings on E side of Church Sq.

Postcard showing five views of High Wycombe - the Parish Church, the Library, Guildhall, the Waterfall on The Rye and the Dyke. High Wycombe. 1950's?
Composite postcard showing five views of High Wycombe. Centre, the Parish Church in Church St. Top left, the Library and gardens with Town Hall beyond, in Queen Victoria Rd. Top right, the Guildhall with the Falcon public house to left, at W end of the High St. Bottom right, the Waterfall on the Dyke at E end of The Rye. Bottom left, The Dyke, seen from Wendover Way looking NW.

Looking NW, a view of the ceremony granting the Freedom of the Borough to the 1st Green Jackets, outside Town Hall, Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. April 1962
The men of the 1st Green Jackets, the 43rd and 52nd, and the Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Light Infantry (TA) lined up in front of the Town Hall for a ceremony granting them the Freedom of the Borough. Under a canopy stands the Mayor, Councillor Hann, together with other dignitaries including the Mace Bearer (Norris) and the Beadle. The Town Hall and adjacent Library are decked with flags. A small crowd looks on. Back right are the shops at E.end of the High St. including Sewmaster in the White House.

Looking N, a view of 'The Drovers' PH public house and, on the opposite side of Drovers Lane, a cottage. Southend, nr Turville. 1930's?
Left, The Drovers public house with the sign at the gateway, standing on Drovers Lane. To the right, a cottage used as the subject for a postcard. Part of an exhibition celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking NE, a view of Alex Stacey's bus 'Bluebird', standing in Queen Victoria Rd, High Wycombe. July 1913
Alex Stacey's bus Bluebird standing in Queen Victoria Rd. The bus number is LC 7313. Behind left is Dial House on the corner of Easton St/Crendon St. See also RHW26054

Looking NW, a view towards the town from the grounds of Wycombe Abbey with the school in the foreground. High Wycombe. c 1960
From the grounds of Wycombe Abbey a view towards the town. The E and S fronts of Wycombe Abbey are shown, with the chapel building to the left. Beyond, the College of Further Education and the tower of the parish church are visible.

Looking N, a view of a man and a child standing before the S porch of All Saints Parish Church. Church Sq, High Wycombe. c 1900
A man and child standing outside the S porch of All Saints Parish Church. The porch was originally Early English, altered later. The statues of the Evangelists were added in 1894 in memory of Edward Wheeler.

Looking SW from the Bassetsbury Lane/Keep Hill Rd junction, a view of a large tree, with Holywell Mead beyond. Bassetsbury area, High Wycombe. c 1980
A large tree off Keep Hill Rd, just after the junction with Bassetsbury Lane. Beyond, Holywell Mead with the Back Stream flowing at the foot of the trees. Centre, the buildings of the Express Dairy.

Looking NE from the Hospital roof, an elevated view of Wycombe Abbey School grounds, Queen Victoria Rd and beyond. High Wycombe. 1965
An elevated view across Wycombe Abbey School grounds, Queen Victoria Rd and beyond; taken from the roof of Wycombe General Hospital during the 'Topping Out' ceremony. Foreground, the school grounds with surrounding wall. Left, the Police Station with the District Council Offices facing. The River Wye flows S of these from W to E. Top left, the railway station.

A view of the High Wycombe Volunteer Fire Brigade with a horse drawn fire engine. The Rye, High Wycombe. c 1900
High Wycombe Volunteer Fire Brigade (founded 1868) with a horse-drawn fire engine on the Rye. Horses provided by Mr L. Weston job and postmaster.[md]

Composite postcard showing seven views of High Wycombe and West Wycombe. 1950's?
Postcard with seven views of High Wycombe and West Wycombe. Left top, Queen Victoria Rd with the Police Station, Town Hall and Library left and Council Offices facing. Top right, both sides of West Wycombe High St, looking W. Centre left, Recreation ground - the Rye, looking N. Centre, elevated view from church tower at West Wycombe, looking E. Centre right, Frogmoor looking N to railway line with shops and a cinema. Bottom left, the Waterfall at E end of the Dyke on The Rye. Bottom right, the Town Hall in Queen Victoria Rd.

Looking SW, a view across the lake to the E front of Wycombe Abbey School, High Wycombe. 1970's?
The E front of Wycombe Abbey School seen from across the lake in the school grounds.

Looking NE, a view of the W and S sides of St. Saviour's Church, Turville Heath. about 1930
W side of St. Saviour's Church with cross in flint-work above window, S. side with one storey extension on the side. Belfry at E. end. Railings surround church yard. Part of an exhibition celebrating the centenary of Turville parish.

Looking SW across the Lake, a view of the E front of Wycombe Abbey School and the Chapel. Wycombe Abbey grounds, High Wycombe. winter 1983
A view across the Lake to the E front of Wycombe Abbey School, with the Chapel just visible beyond.. In the background (left), other school buildings fronting onto Marlow Hill.

Looking S, a view of the yard behind the Coach and Horses PH, later demolished, at the E end of Easton St, High Wycombe. Easter 1968
Cycles propped against the wall in the yard behind the Coach and Horses public house at no. 40 Easton St. in 1968. Left, a single storey building with dormer windows garage doors with loft door above. Centre the carriage arch leading to Easton St. Later demolished to make way for new road development.

Looking NW, a copy of an engraving showing soldiers on parade on the S lawns of Wycombe Abbey, High Wycombe. 1854
Copy of an engraving showing a military parade on the S side of Wycombe Abbey. The soldiers, in square formation, are watched by men and women. Also seen on BFP04230

Looking SW across A40, a view of machinery working on the site of the former almshouses in Easton St, High Wycombe. c 1970
Machinery working on the demolition of the former almshouses at the E. end of Easton St. Foreground, an arch of St. Johns Hospital. Centre, Wycombe General Hospital with nurses' quarters behind.

Looking S, a view of Abbey Way roundabout in the foreground, with girls leaving the front entrance of Wycombe Abbey School beyond. High Wycombe. early 1970's
Girls leaving the front entrance of Wycombe Abbey School with Abbey Way and the roundabout in the foreground.

Looking W along the front of Wycombe General Hospital, a parade of 16 flags held by servicemen and women at a ceremony, Queen Alexandra Rd, High Wycombe. 1970's.
Sixteen flags held by servicemen and women including members of the British legion at a ceremony at the front of Wycombe General Hospital. Off left probably the Ercol Band. See RHW02567

Looking N, a view of Trinity United Reformed Church and nos. 1 - 5 London Rd, High Wycombe. Oct 1979
Trinity United Reformed Church Easton St. and nos. 1 - 5 London Rd. a terrace of 18C houses standing on the A40. Left a pathway leading onto The Rye passing by the restored Pann Mill.

mentions.ne_span: Trinity United Reformed Church Easton St.

text:
Looking SW to entrance of Wycombe General Hospital, the Ercol Band with priests at a ceremony. Queen Alexandra Rd, High Wycombe. 1970's
A ceremony led by a priest with two others alongside at the entrance of Wycombe General Hospital. The Ercol Band plays right.

Looking NW, with part of Lucas Wood shown on right and odd numbered houses just beyond. Lucas Road, High Wycombe. February 1980
A view along Lucas Rd with Lucas Wood shown on right and odd numbered houses just beyond.

Looking NE at junction with multi-storey car park entrance road, a view of a red telephone box. Easton St, High Wycombe. winter 1987/88
Red telephone box of Giles Gilbert Scott design standing on N side of Easton St at the junction with the entrance road to the multi storey car park. Building on right was the former Post Office.

Looking S to entrance wall, commemorative plaques outside Wycombe General Hospital, Queen Alexandra Rd, High Wycombe. 1978
Plaque to left of RHW02564 originally placed at the entrance to the High Wycombe and District War Memorial Hospital. Inscriptions on the plaques reads - 'The High Wycombe and District War Memorial Hospital. The Great War 1914 - 1918. To the glorious memory of the brave men whose names are here recorded who at the call of king and country left all that was dear to them, endured hardship, faced danger and finally passed out of the sight of men by the path of duty and self-sacrifice, giving up their own lives that others might live in freedom. At the going down of the sun and in the morning, we will remember them.' 'This hospital was opened by Field-Marshal Sir William Robertson, BT., G.C.B., G.C.M.G., K.G.V.O., December 9th 1923'

mentions.ne_span: High Wycombe and District War Memorial Hospital

View of an explanatory plaque, adjacent to the WW I commemorative plaques outside Wycombe General Hospital, Queen Alexandra Rd, High Wycombe. 1978
A plaque placed at the top right of the set of World War I memorial plaques at the entrance to Wycombe General Hospital. Inscription states - 'These plaques and commemorative stones were originally placed at the entrance to the High Wycombe and District Memorial Hospital which was sited further up Marlow Hill. They were removed in 1971 when work started on the third phase of Wycombe General Hospital. The first hospital in this locality was established in 1875 on Amersham Hill and was called the High Wycombe Cottage Hospital the name being changed in 1891 to the High Wycombe and Earl of Beaconsfield Memorial Cottage Hospital. It was closed in 1922 when the High Wycombe and District War Memorial Hospital opened on Marlow Hill. The present Hospital first admitted patients in 1966.'

The man immediately behind the Captain (who is wearing a cap) is Frank Harman, who was wounded three times in WWI. In December 1917 he was transferred to the Tank Corps and was involved in the ''Battle of the Woods'' in August 1918. Frank was demobbed in January 1919 and returned to Wycombe to resume his pre-war occupation as a Writer, Grainer and Guilder.

In the back row, far right is Frank Darby holding his daughter Diann, with Dick Jones to his right. In front of him are Jim and Flo Bowers.To the left of Flo is Sophia Bowers, the party organiser.
